passages.text: FY25 below on inventory charges, cash flow in- line; Havieron progressing; Neutral

GGP reported segment EBITDA of A\\$527mn, below expectations on inventory charges (while not included in reported unit costs on acquisition treatment, GGP still recognised inventory charges through the P&L), with an overall group EBITDA margin of \(48\%\) . NPAT of \(\sim \mathsf{A}\mathsf{S}337\mathsf{mn}\) was below GSe albeit above Consensus on lower D&A (which is expected to remain lower near- term as Telfer mine life extends (longer useful life), and Havieron remains under construction). GGP finished FY25 with cash of \(\sim \mathsf{A}\mathsf{S}575\mathsf{mn}\) (pre- reported) whilst remaining debt free, with total liquidity of \(\sim \mathsf{A}\mathsf{S}650\mathsf{mn}\) .

FY26 guidance remains unchanged from the 4Q25 result at 260- 310koz and AISC of A\\$2,400- 2,800/oz. At Havieron, focus still remains on the pending Feasibility Study (FS), which continues to progress and remains targeted for completion in the Dec- 25 quarter (we note GGP recently received WA environmental approval for Tailings extension and mobile crushing to support Havieron road construction).

Though GGP is trading at a longer- term discount after factoring Telfer extension opportunities ( \(\sim 0.9x\) NAV or pricing \(\sim \mathsf{US}\$ 2,710 / \mathsf{oz}\) gold; peers \(\sim 1x\) NAV and \(\sim \mathsf{US}\$ 2,930 / \mathsf{oz}\) ), we remain Neutral rated and cautious on the increased Telfer uncertainty and Havieron likely to see cost/capex increases. FCF yield remains positive in FY26E at \(\sim 8\%\) , though drops to \(\sim 10\%\) over FY27/28E on increasing capex spend on Telfer extension/Havieron development ramp up, before improving to \(\sim 10\%\) from FY30E.

We rate GGP a Neutral on:

1. Valuation: Though GGP is trading at a longer-term discount after factoring Telfer extension opportunities, we remain cautious on the increased Telfer uncertainty and Havieron is likely to see cost/capex increases, with the stock trading on \(\sim 0.9x\) NAV, or pricing \(\sim \mathrm{US\$2,710 / oz}\) gold (peer average \(\sim 1x\) NAV and \(\sim \mathrm{US\$2,930 / oz}\) ). FCF yield remains positive in FY26E at \(\sim 8\%\) , though drops to \(\sim 5 - 10\%\) over FY27/28E on increasing capex spend on Telfer extension/Havieron development ramp up, before improving to \(\sim 10\%\) from FY30E.

2. Near-term production rebound, before medium-term growth from Havieron ramp up: We forecast a rebound in gold production to \(\sim 300kz\) in FY26E, and expect a revised FY27+ outlook with the Havieron Feasibility Study (FS) in the Dec-25 quarter (where we factor in \(\sim \mathrm{A\$1bn}\) remaining spend to first gold in FY28E, with the second decline/expansion from \(\sim 2.8M\) tpa to \(\sim 4.3M\) tpa in FY31E costing a further \(\mathrm{A\$0.5 - 0.6bn}\) ). Over the medium-term, we see the Telfer extension supporting an overlap of ore sourcing and prolonged utilisation of both processing trains (growing gold production to \(\sim 350kz\) pa from FY29E) before dropping to a single train from \(\sim \mathrm{FY31E}\) .

3. Operating cashflow to self-fund growth, with net cash position supporting capital returns prospects: We see net cash growing further to \(\sim \mathrm{A\$0.8bn}\) in FY26E. With existing and potential additional debt capacity for Havieron (GGP has received a non-binding letter of support from a Tier 1 banking syndicate for \(\mathrm{A\$775mn}\) in proposed banking facilities to fund the Havieron development and operations ( \(\mathrm{A\$650mn}\) seven-year term debt; \(\mathrm{A\$100mn}\) five-year revolver; and \(\mathrm{A\$25mn}\) five-year contingent instrument facility), as line of site on Havieron/Telfer spend improves we see potential supporting accelerated capital returns in the form of buybacks/dividends (where we factor in a \(\sim 1 - 2\%\) yield from \(\sim \mathrm{FY29E}\) ).

The Goldman Sachs Factor Profile provides investment context for a stock by comparing key attributes to the market (i.e. our universe of rated stocks) and its sector peers. The four key attributes depicted are: Growth, Financial Returns, Multiple (e.g. valuation) and Integrated (a composite of Growth, Financial Returns and Multiple). Growth, Financial Returns and Multiple are calculated by using normalized ranks for specific metrics for each stock. The normalized ranks for the metrics are then averaged and converted into percentiles for the relevant attribute. The precise calculation of each metric may vary depending on the fiscal year, industry and region, but the standard approach is as follows:

Growth is based on a stock's forward- looking sales growth, EBITDA growth and EPS growth (for financial stocks, only EPS and sales growth), with a higher percentile indicating a higher growth company. Financial Returns is based on a stock's forward- looking ROE, ROCE and CROCI (for financial stocks, only ROE), with a higher percentile indicating a company with higher financial returns. Multiple is based on a stock's forward- looking P/E, P/B, price/dividend (P/D), EV/EBITDA, EV/FCF and EV/Debt Adjusted Cash Flow (DACF) (for financial stocks, only P/E, P/B and P/D), with a higher percentile indicating a stock trading at a higher multiple. The Integrated percentile is calculated as the average of the Growth percentile, Financial Returns percentile and (100% - Multiple percentile).

Financial Returns and Multiple use the Goldman Sachs analyst forecasts at the fiscal year- end at least three quarters in the future. Growth uses inputs for the fiscal year at least seven quarters in the future compared with the year at least three quarters in the future (on a per- share basis for all metrics).
For a more detailed description of how we calculate the GS Factor Profile, please contact your GS representative.

Across our global coverage, we examine stocks using an M&A framework, considering both qualitative factors and quantitative factors (which may vary across sectors and regions) to incorporate the potential that certain companies could be acquired. We then assign a M&A rank as a means of scoring companies under our rated coverage from 1 to 3, with 1 representing high (30%- 50%) probability of the company becoming an acquisition target, 2 representing medium (15%- 30%) probability and 3 representing low (0%- 15%) probability. For companies ranked 1 or 2, in line with our standard departmental guidelines we incorporate an M&A component into our target price. M&A rank of 3 is considered immaterial and therefore does not factor into our price target, and may or may not be discussed in research.
